(Staffordshire).","English (West Midlands): topographic name for someone who lived by a spring or stream, northern Middle English <i>wall(e)</i> (Old English (Mercian) <i>wæll(a)</i>; compare   Well  ).","Irish (of Norman origin): Anglicized form of <i>de Valle</i> (Gaelicized form <i>de Bhál</i>), the name of a Norman family established in Munster and Connacht."],"variants":[{"name":"Wallander","meanings":["Swedish: variant of   Wall  , with the addition of the suffix <i>-ander</i>, derived from Greek <i>anēr</i> (genitive <i>andros</i>) ‘man’."]},{"name":"Wallenberg","meanings":["Swedish: ornamental name composed of the elements   Wall   + the plural suffix <i>- en</i> (originally German) + <i>berg</i> ‘mountain, hill’.","History: While working as a businessman in Budapest in 1944, Raoul Wallenberg (1912–?47) was entrusted by the Swedish government with the protection of Hungarian Jews from the Nazis. Wallenberg helped about 95,000 Jews to escape death by issuing them Swedish passports. When Soviet forces took control of Budapest in 1945, he was arrested, taken to Moscow, and imprisoned. The Soviet authorities stated that he died in prison in 1947."]},{"name":"Well","meanings":["English (London): topographic name for someone who lived near a spring or stream, from Middle English <i>well(e)</i> ‘spring, stream, well’ (Old English <i>well(a)</i>).","German: from a short form of the personal names <i>Wallo</i>, <i>Walilo</i>.","German: nickname from Middle High German <i>wël</i> ‘round’."]},{"name":"Walle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Alberto, Arnulfo, Efrain, Emilia, Evodio, Frederico, Jaime, Javier, Jesus, Jose, Juan, Justo.","English and German: variant of   Wall  . This surname is also found in Mexico.","Norwegian: variant of   Valle  ."]},{"name":"Wallen","meanings":["Swedish (mainly <b>Wallén</b>): topographic or ornamental name composed of a variant of the element <i>vall</i> ‘grassy bank, pasture’ (see   Wall  ) or the root of Latin <i>vallis</i> ‘valley’ (representing Swedish <i>dal</i>) + the adjectival suffix <i>-én/-en</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>-enius</i> ‘relating to’. Compare   Wallin   and   Walen  ."]},{"name":"Walls","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Wall  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish (Derry): in Ireland this name is also sometimes a variant of   Walsh  ."]}]},{"name":"Karen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of   Katherine .  It was first introduced to the English-speaking world by Scandinavian settlers in America; it has been used in Britain only since the 1940s, but had become very popular by the 1960s."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705208,"age":1,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705210,"age":14,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705212,"age":34,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower 